        <div class=3D"wp-block-gds-faq-accordion-item__accordion-content-in=
ner" itemprop=3D"text">
         =20

<p>How to convert a Fahrenheit temperature to Celsius temperature in your h=
ead?</p>



<p>To convert Fahrenheit to Celsius:</p>



<p><strong>Step 1</strong>: Remove 32 =C2=B0F from the =C2=B0F temperature.=
</p>



<p><strong>Step 2</strong>: Multiply the =C2=B0F with 5/9. What? Ok, this i=
s maybe too difficult, as 5/9 is 0.555555. But we can get pretty close if w=
e divide it by 2 and then add 10 % (to be exact we should add 11.11 %).</p>



<p><strong>Examples:</strong></p>



<p>What is 100 =C2=B0F in =C2=B0C?</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Remove 32 =C2=B0F =3D&gt; 100 =E2=80=93 32 =3D 68.</li>



<li>Divide 68 with 2 =3D 34.</li>



<li>Add 10 % =3D&gt; 34 + 3.4 =3D 37.4.</li>



<li>So, 100 =C2=B0F is roughly 37.4 =C2=B0C.</li>
</ul>



<p>If we want to make it more precise (and we always do!), we can add 11%&n=
bsp; instead of 10%. In practice, this is easiest to do by first adding 10 =
% and then adding another 1 %. So, let=E2=80=99s redo the above example:</p=
>



<p>What is 100 =C2=B0F in =C2=B0C?</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Remove 32 =C2=B0F =3D&gt; 100 =E2=80=93 32 =3D 68.</li>



<li>Divide 68 with 2 =3D 34.</li>



<li>Add 10 % =3D&gt; 34 + 3.4 =3D 37.4.</li>



<li>Add another 1% =3D&gt; 37.4 + 0.374 =3D 37. 77 =C2=B0C.</li>



<li>So, we can round it up by saying 100 =C2=B0F equals 37.8 =C2=B0C.</li>
</ul>


